WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:24.107 --> 00:26.316
[FOREBODING MUSIC]

00:51.092 --> 00:53.010
[ERIC:]
At the beginning of time

00:54.387 --> 00:55.929
the clock struck one.

00:57.557 --> 01:00.267
A drop of dew and
the clock struck two.

01:03.438 --> 01:04.980
From the dew grew a tree

01:06.483 --> 01:08.317
and the clock struck three.

01:10.653 --> 01:12.237
Then the tree made a door

01:14.157 --> 01:15.824
and the clock struck four.

01:17.869 --> 01:19.119
Then man came alive

01:21.498 --> 01:23.248
and the clock struck five.

01:26.586 --> 01:27.836
Count not

01:29.130 --> 01:30.255
waste not

01:31.674 --> 01:33.217
the hours on the clock.

01:35.678 --> 01:38.138
Behold I stand
at the door and knock.

01:41.226 --> 01:44.019
[MUSIC BUILDS UP]

01:56.032 --> 02:00.077
[CLICKS OF TRAIN WHEELS
ON TRACKS]

02:29.399 --> 02:31.400
[MUSIC STOPS]

02:33.361 --> 02:35.529
Is that a new Bradshaw's, Eric?

02:37.073 --> 02:40.367
Or one of your world famous collection
of out of date railway timetables?

02:40.451 --> 02:42.119
[THE MEN CHUCKLE]

02:44.247 --> 02:45.873
I have a small problem...

02:49.752 --> 02:53.338
which I suspect this gathering
might find interesting.

02:56.968 --> 02:58.260
Last Thursday

02:58.761 --> 03:01.680
I was returning from
a book auction in Chester

03:02.004 --> 03:04.285
and, learning of a delay
on the Manchester-Edinburgh line,

03:04.309 --> 03:08.270
found it necessary to make
a rapid adjustment to my itinerary,

03:08.479 --> 03:12.274
leaving me just three minutes
to change platforms at Crewe.

03:21.701 --> 03:23.619
[SLOW INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC]

03:44.432 --> 03:46.600
[CONDUCTOR:]
Tickets from Crewe.

03:47.352 --> 03:48.727
Tickets from Crewe.

03:50.271 --> 03:52.314
You're on the wrong train, sir.
This is for Glasgow.

03:52.398 --> 03:53.899
The Edinburgh train...
It's delayed. I thought

03:53.983 --> 03:55.943
if I got your train as far as
Carstairs I ought to be

03:56.027 --> 03:58.403
in time to catch the
Manchester-Edinburgh on its way up.

03:59.656 --> 04:01.990
That should work.
Enjoy your journey, sir.

04:03.076 --> 04:04.785
Tickets from Crewe.

04:05.411 --> 04:08.664
I could have done with you
this morning, in Taunton.

04:10.583 --> 04:12.793
Straight forward enough, surely?

04:12.961 --> 04:16.880
Train down
to Bristol Temple Meads...
The Bristol train
was cancelled.

04:17.048 --> 04:18.928
Well in that case you could
take it across to...

04:18.966 --> 04:21.426
A friend gave me a lift.

04:24.764 --> 04:26.807
I see.
And he gave me
a timetable.

04:26.891 --> 04:28.600
[PATTI LAUGHS] Look at this...

04:28.685 --> 04:31.853
He marked all of the
interesting things on the map.

04:34.732 --> 04:35.899
Did you know...

04:36.567 --> 04:38.819
Warrington was famous for vodka?

04:42.615 --> 04:44.574
It's also the birthplace
of George Formby.

04:45.827 --> 04:47.995
Hmm... is it really?

04:48.079 --> 04:50.330
Most people assume it was Wigan.

04:51.165 --> 04:52.374
Or Formby.

04:54.585 --> 04:56.378
But it was Warrington.

05:02.367 --> 05:05.447
You know, with all due respect to your
friend, if all he's mentioned is vodka,

05:05.471 --> 05:08.974
he's really only scratched
the surface of Warrington.

05:09.851 --> 05:11.018
The Black Prince.

05:11.311 --> 05:12.978
Remember the Black Prince?

05:13.354 --> 05:15.314
Had all his armour made there.

05:15.398 --> 05:18.358
Warrington was really the only place to go
if you wanted a suit of armour.

05:19.360 --> 05:21.361
A sort of Saville Row in steel.

05:21.738 --> 05:23.280
[LAUGHS]

05:26.117 --> 05:27.242
Goodness!

05:27.535 --> 05:30.454
Maybe we should get off,
take a look around.

05:31.956 --> 05:36.001
Well if think Warrington's interesting,
you wait till we get to Preston.

05:36.085 --> 05:38.003
[LIGHT MUSIC]

05:46.220 --> 05:47.220
Lancaster,

05:48.723 --> 05:50.390
known as the Hanging Town.

05:51.809 --> 05:55.812
Lancaster Assizes hanged more
people than any court in the land,

05:55.938 --> 05:57.356
except for London.

05:59.859 --> 06:01.318
That's Carnforth.

06:01.944 --> 06:04.654
That's where they filmed
Brief Encounter, apparently.

06:04.822 --> 06:06.582
You're too young to
remember that, of course.

06:06.824 --> 06:10.744
Well my Aunt went to see it with
a girlfriend and a couple of sailors,

06:10.828 --> 06:12.496
and she told me that...

06:12.997 --> 06:14.998
whenever the actress...

06:15.083 --> 06:16.958
Celia Johnson.
Celia Johnson...

06:17.043 --> 06:19.753
got a bit tearful,
the sailors would shout,

06:19.837 --> 06:21.713
"Come on, Trevor.
Give her one!"

06:24.634 --> 06:25.634
Sorry.

06:26.260 --> 06:27.677
I've gone too far.

06:28.763 --> 06:31.473
Promise I'll behave
better from now on.

06:31.557 --> 06:32.974
[LAUGHS]

06:34.477 --> 06:35.644
[CLEARS HER THROAT]

06:37.313 --> 06:40.565
I've never been to the Highlands
before, so suddenly... um...

06:40.691 --> 06:44.319
well finding myself single again,
so to speak,

06:44.404 --> 06:46.863
I... I thought I'd like
to see them.

06:47.448 --> 06:50.617
So I'm going to go up as far as
Mallaig by train and then I'm catching

06:50.701 --> 06:54.079
the coach to Inverness
and coming down the other side.

06:54.163 --> 06:55.288
What do you think?

06:55.665 --> 06:57.416
The West Coast is
extraordinarily beautiful.

06:57.500 --> 06:59.543
You might well fall in love with it.

07:01.003 --> 07:03.630
And if I were to fall in love,
what then?

07:06.217 --> 07:08.301
Well instead of a coach
to Inverness,

07:08.386 --> 07:11.430
you might consider taking the line
back to Tyndrum and changing for Oban.

07:11.848 --> 07:14.266
And from there you can get
any number of boat trips:

07:14.350 --> 07:15.725
Iona, Staffa.

07:17.353 --> 07:18.728
It's very romantic.

07:22.024 --> 07:23.316
Are you romantic?

07:29.991 --> 07:32.075
I have to be in Edinburgh...

07:33.244 --> 07:34.369
by Wednesday.

07:36.456 --> 07:38.957
[ANNOUNCER:]
Carstairs, now approaching.

07:39.041 --> 07:41.376
Carstairs.
Carstairs.

07:44.589 --> 07:45.839
So it is.

07:55.600 --> 07:57.350
It was very nice to meet you.

07:59.562 --> 08:01.438
You were an unexpected bonus.

08:04.108 --> 08:05.108
Well.

08:06.027 --> 08:07.110
Thank you again.

08:23.753 --> 08:25.003
[ERIC:]
And so you see,

08:26.839 --> 08:29.591
I am forced
to the unlikely conclusion,

08:30.676 --> 08:32.594
that I've fallen in love.

08:39.268 --> 08:40.309
[MUSIC PAUSES]

08:40.477 --> 08:41.477
So?

08:43.063 --> 08:44.814
What are you going to do?

08:49.946 --> 08:52.113
Would you excuse me for a moment?

08:54.200 --> 08:57.744
There are only two trains from Inverness
to Edinburgh on Wednesdays...

08:57.828 --> 08:59.829
[MUSIC RESUMES]

09:01.249 --> 09:04.960
[ANNOUNCER:] Edinburgh Waverley,
this is Edinburgh Waverley.

09:26.315 --> 09:27.732
[MUSIC STOPS]

09:27.942 --> 09:29.025
Good afternoon.

09:30.903 --> 09:32.529
Good afternoon. Ah...

09:33.114 --> 09:35.824
This is a surprise.
What a coincidence.

09:37.910 --> 09:39.995
Are you catching this train?

09:40.496 --> 09:41.788
Yes, I am.

09:42.498 --> 09:45.041
Well it's just that it terminates here.

09:47.336 --> 09:49.713
It's not entirely a coincidence.

09:52.425 --> 09:54.509
It's not entirely a surprise.

09:57.013 --> 09:59.556
I'm not really used to entertaining,
as you'll see.

10:04.270 --> 10:05.562
What are you doing?

10:05.980 --> 10:07.522
I was just going to give it a stir.

10:08.149 --> 10:09.190
Good heavens.

10:09.275 --> 10:12.068
But the bottom of the pan's
going to burn...
Sit down.

10:12.153 --> 10:13.361
So masterful.

10:14.280 --> 10:16.072
[TICKING]

10:17.450 --> 10:19.784
Masterful but wrong.
We shall see.

10:20.995 --> 10:23.455
I might nip out for a Brillo pad
for the burn marks

10:23.539 --> 10:25.165
on the bottom of the pan.
Don't move.

10:26.042 --> 10:27.584
Why not?

10:29.170 --> 10:30.920
Because I'm looking at you.

10:41.557 --> 10:43.475
[TIMER SOUNDS OFF]

10:51.859 --> 10:53.026
Perfect.

11:04.455 --> 11:06.373
You're making
quite a meal of this.

11:06.457 --> 11:08.291
That was the general idea.

11:10.628 --> 11:12.295
You know, I was wondering.

11:22.223 --> 11:24.849
I've never kissed a man
with a moustache before.

11:24.934 --> 11:26.142
Hmm...

11:26.477 --> 11:30.397
And I don't think I'm going to kiss
a man with a moustache again.

11:32.733 --> 11:34.150
Hmm.

11:36.445 --> 11:38.988
And if the man
removed the moustache?

11:40.199 --> 11:41.908
Yes, that would do nicely.

11:46.288 --> 11:48.206
[LAUGHS]

11:49.250 --> 11:52.127
[SLOW INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC]

12:32.585 --> 12:35.837
I'm just going to keep looking
into those lovely brown eyes.

12:37.047 --> 12:38.381
Why?

12:39.258 --> 12:40.508
I don't know.

12:44.472 --> 12:47.557
Takes my mind off the broken teeth
and the shabby clothes.

12:54.023 --> 12:56.399
Not quite so shabby today,
actually.

12:59.779 --> 13:02.405
Better get them off so
I don't get confused, then.

13:02.490 --> 13:04.574
If you think
that's a good idea.
M-hmm.

13:13.083 --> 13:14.626
I'm so happy.

13:30.684 --> 13:32.560
[MUSIC STOPS]

13:32.645 --> 13:34.312
[WATER TRICKLES]

13:34.480 --> 13:36.314
[BOOT STEPS IN]

13:36.398 --> 13:39.818
[FOREBODING ORIENTAL MUSIC]

13:42.780 --> 13:44.697
Get dressed, Lomax.

14:17.273 --> 14:18.982
[SHOUTS IN JAPANESE]

14:37.293 --> 14:39.502
[YELLS IN JAPANESE]

14:43.173 --> 14:44.716
No, no, no.

14:45.968 --> 14:50.638
No!

14:51.390 --> 14:53.766
The war's over!
Not for you, Lomax.

14:53.851 --> 14:55.435
No! No!
This way, please.

14:58.647 --> 15:00.732
Please... no!

15:04.904 --> 15:06.571
Eric!
Oh, God!

15:09.116 --> 15:11.743
[ERIC CONTINUES YELLING
IN AGONY]

15:29.511 --> 15:30.803
[STATIC IN EARPHONES]

15:32.014 --> 15:35.433
[VOICE FROM EARPHONES:]
Help us! For the love of God,
someone help us!

15:35.517 --> 15:39.103
[YELLS AND SHOUTS FROM
EARPHONES CONTINUE]

15:45.653 --> 15:49.948
Gentlemen.

15:52.576 --> 15:54.410
You have all fought valiantly.

15:54.495 --> 15:56.663
You are a credit
to your country.

15:56.914 --> 16:00.208
But I have to inform you that
General Percival has decided,

16:00.292 --> 16:03.544
under the circumstances,
to negotiate, as it were,

16:03.712 --> 16:04.712
a ceasefire.

16:06.465 --> 16:08.841
He's thrown in the towel, sir?
What happens to us?

16:08.926 --> 16:09.676
Thorlby!

16:09.843 --> 16:12.428
We are still a fighting unit and
you will do what you're told.

16:13.180 --> 16:16.808
You can start by destroying anything
that might be of value to the enemy.

16:17.267 --> 16:18.643
Quickly, gentlemen.

16:24.525 --> 16:25.525
Lomax.

16:25.609 --> 16:26.776
What are you doing?

16:27.528 --> 16:29.237
Might come in handy, sir.

16:30.239 --> 16:31.531
[SCOFFS]

16:35.661 --> 16:37.412
[SUSPENSFUL DRUM ROLLS]

16:41.375 --> 16:43.626
[AEROPLANE ENGINES RUMBLE]

16:44.461 --> 16:45.628
Christ almighty.

16:46.213 --> 16:47.714
[TANK ENGINES RUMBLE]

16:51.969 --> 16:54.178
[YELLS IN JAPANESE]

17:13.323 --> 17:14.906
Lomax, my friend,

17:15.826 --> 17:20.038
I think we have just witnessed
the fall of the British Empire.

17:29.465 --> 17:30.923
[SHOUTS IN JAPANESE]

17:31.050 --> 17:32.842
You will number off!

17:33.385 --> 17:35.261
Beginning with number one.

17:37.056 --> 17:38.139
One.

17:38.223 --> 17:39.223
Two.

17:39.892 --> 17:41.059
Three.

17:41.143 --> 17:42.143
Four.

17:42.853 --> 17:44.145
Five.

17:44.480 --> 17:45.646
Six.

17:45.731 --> 17:46.731
Seven.

17:47.524 --> 17:48.733
Eight.

17:49.068 --> 17:50.443
Nine.

17:50.861 --> 17:51.861
Ten.

17:54.573 --> 17:55.573
Jack.

17:57.117 --> 17:58.117
Queen.

17:59.078 --> 18:00.078
King.

18:01.205 --> 18:02.205
Ace.

18:03.123 --> 18:04.916
[COMMANDS IN JAPANESE]

18:07.419 --> 18:10.171
[SOMBRE MUSIC INTERRUPTED
WITH SHOUTS IN JAPANESE]

18:17.846 --> 18:18.930
Good?

18:21.517 --> 18:23.184
[COMMANDS IN JAPANESE]

18:24.978 --> 18:27.146
[HEAVY DOORS CLOSE]

18:35.155 --> 18:37.073
[METAL CLANG, SILENCE]

18:49.378 --> 18:51.379
[SLOW MUSIC]

18:53.340 --> 18:55.633
[DISTANT WAVES]

19:15.529 --> 19:17.196
So what do you think?

19:17.573 --> 19:19.949
I don't want
to take over completely.

19:22.953 --> 19:25.663
You're tired.
Do you want a cup of tea?

19:52.649 --> 19:54.442
[MUSIC STOPS]

19:54.568 --> 19:56.861
[DISTANT THUNDER]

20:05.370 --> 20:08.039
[BREATHES RAPIDLY]

20:13.003 --> 20:14.420
Eric?

20:27.142 --> 20:29.644
[CLATTER]

20:37.569 --> 20:38.986
What have you done?

20:41.531 --> 20:44.951
I decided, on reflection,
I preferred things
the way they were.

20:45.285 --> 20:48.829
Eric, whatever's wrong,
you can talk to me about it.

20:49.081 --> 20:50.081
Eric.

20:51.792 --> 20:56.045
Please. Never, ever try to interfere
with matters that don't concern you.

20:58.257 --> 20:59.715
There's no objection, I hope?

21:00.634 --> 21:02.677
No. No, of course not.

21:09.559 --> 21:10.851
[KNOCKS]

21:11.061 --> 21:14.897
Eric?

21:15.065 --> 21:18.067
I was just wondering
if you'd paid these bills.

21:52.477 --> 21:55.062
[LOW FOREBODING MUSIC]

22:35.562 --> 22:36.562
Eric?

22:39.983 --> 22:41.400
Eric.

22:57.626 --> 22:59.877
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

23:02.047 --> 23:03.798
Mrs Lomax?
Mike Moffat,

23:03.882 --> 23:06.509
Northumberland Debt Recovery.
Non-payment of rates.

23:07.052 --> 23:10.262
These gentlemen are here
to help me. Is Mr Lomax at home?

23:10.389 --> 23:12.139
Non-payment?
That's right, madam.

23:12.265 --> 23:14.892
You may be aware we have visited
on two previous occasions.

23:14.976 --> 23:16.519
No. No, I wasn't aware.
Look, my husband...

23:16.603 --> 23:18.963
And those visits were made
after all attempts to communicate

23:18.980 --> 23:20.940
with Mr Lomax by post
had failed.

23:21.024 --> 23:23.818
I'm sorry, I really know
nothing about this.

23:23.985 --> 23:25.694
But if you could
possibly leave it with me.

23:25.779 --> 23:27.780
My husband is slightly
disorganised sometimes...

23:27.864 --> 23:30.408
Are you in a position
to make a payment now, madam?

23:32.035 --> 23:34.578
[MUSIC BUILDS UP]

23:43.171 --> 23:44.588
We are authorised to enter

23:44.673 --> 23:46.393
the property and make
an inventory of goods.

23:46.466 --> 23:47.925
You can't come in here.

23:50.720 --> 23:51.762
Eric. No!

23:51.847 --> 23:53.055
[SCREAM]

23:53.765 --> 23:55.015
Drop it!
No, please!

23:55.183 --> 23:56.767
Drop the knife!

23:56.810 --> 23:58.060
Drop it, sir!

24:01.440 --> 24:02.523
Eric!

24:03.150 --> 24:04.233
Eric, stop!

24:04.443 --> 24:06.986
Please, why won't you
talk to me?

24:09.489 --> 24:10.573
Eric!

24:11.908 --> 24:13.868
[MUSIC SLOWS DOWN]

24:15.662 --> 24:17.955
Eric, we can't live like this.

24:22.502 --> 24:24.753
No, leave me. I'm fine!

24:31.011 --> 24:32.470
[BRAKES LIGHTLY SQUEAL]

24:56.369 --> 24:58.162
Fourteenth of next month,
Burton.

24:58.246 --> 24:59.455
Same time.
Alright.

24:59.539 --> 25:02.333
Put it in your diary.
Aye, thank you Uncle.

25:08.423 --> 25:09.423
Mr Finlay.

25:12.886 --> 25:13.969
Mrs Lomax.

25:18.391 --> 25:20.684
I want to know what
happened to Eric.

25:21.269 --> 25:23.687
You have to talk to Eric.
I have.

25:23.772 --> 25:25.189
And he changes the subject...

25:25.273 --> 25:27.816
whenever we get close to...

25:29.736 --> 25:34.198
He gets as far as the fall of Singapore
and then he just... he shuts down.

25:35.575 --> 25:37.117
[SIGHS]

25:39.162 --> 25:40.496
And then he won't...

25:41.289 --> 25:44.208
he won't talk about
the railway. There's...

25:44.417 --> 25:45.709
I don't know.

25:47.045 --> 25:49.630
[TAKES DEEP BREATH]

25:53.593 --> 25:54.760
I was a nurse.

25:55.387 --> 25:56.762
Twenty years.

25:58.056 --> 26:00.140
I've seen... a lot of suffering.

26:03.812 --> 26:06.397
You can do something
if you know what's wrong.

26:08.275 --> 26:10.985
I'm sorry I can't help you
play Florence Nightingale.

26:11.653 --> 26:15.990
But a lot of men went through something
you can't even begin to imagine.

26:16.324 --> 26:19.827
You're going to have to let us just
get on and cope with it

26:19.911 --> 26:21.161
as best we can.

26:21.246 --> 26:22.955
My husband isn't coping.

26:23.999 --> 26:25.291
He's a mess.

26:28.211 --> 26:31.463
War leaves a mark, Mrs Lomax.

26:32.966 --> 26:36.135
But I don't believe in this
code of silence that you have.

26:36.219 --> 26:37.803
I really don't.

26:38.888 --> 26:41.599
And you may be determined to stay
screwed up and suffer for the rest

26:41.683 --> 26:45.853
of your life, but I don't want that
for Eric. And I can't live like that.

26:46.771 --> 26:48.439
He's a wonderful man.

26:49.024 --> 26:50.024
I've seen it.

26:50.108 --> 26:52.151
I love him and I want him back.

27:01.578 --> 27:02.953
When we came home,

27:04.456 --> 27:06.081
Eric couldn't handle it.

27:08.960 --> 27:10.794
So he joined the Colonial Service,

27:10.879 --> 27:13.047
and built a dam in Africa.

27:15.050 --> 27:16.300
[CHUCKLES]

27:18.470 --> 27:20.971
He wrote to me saying
they had a narrow gauge

27:21.056 --> 27:25.976
railway system and badly needed
more engines and rolling stock.

27:27.187 --> 27:29.855
But only the Japanese
had the right kind,

27:30.940 --> 27:33.025
so he was going to do without.

27:36.696 --> 27:38.572
When he came back, he'd...

27:39.366 --> 27:42.534
he'd come to these meetings
and just sit there.

27:44.454 --> 27:45.871
Didn't talk at all.

27:47.874 --> 27:48.916
He did anything

27:49.000 --> 27:50.584
to avoid people.

27:51.378 --> 27:55.631
Went round and round the country
collecting railway memorabilia.

27:55.882 --> 27:57.633
I think that's how he met you.

28:05.684 --> 28:07.893
His whole life has been trains.

28:07.977 --> 28:10.979
[TRAIN SLOWLY
RUMBLES INTO MOTION]

28:11.064 --> 28:13.524
[FAST PACED MUSIC]

28:36.881 --> 28:38.674
[BREATHES HEAVILY]

28:49.769 --> 28:52.521
[TRAIN THUMPS TO A HALT]

28:52.605 --> 28:53.939
[LOW STEAM HISS]

28:54.023 --> 28:55.274
[BRITISH SOLDIERS:]
Here! Here!

28:56.443 --> 28:57.735
Here!

28:58.945 --> 28:59.945
Water!

29:00.697 --> 29:01.697
Here!

29:03.324 --> 29:05.868
[LOW CHATTER IN JAPANESE]

29:07.787 --> 29:09.204
Here! Water, please!

29:11.416 --> 29:13.542
[YELLS IN JAPANESE]

29:18.757 --> 29:20.132
[CRASH]

29:25.638 --> 29:28.140
[TRAIN SQUEALS INTO MOTION]

29:28.224 --> 29:29.933
[MUSIC BUILDS UP]

29:38.818 --> 29:42.029
[STEAM HISS, WHEELS SQUEAL,
TRAIN STOPS]

29:45.575 --> 29:48.911
[DOOR OPENS,
JAPANESE SOLDIER YELLS]

29:55.043 --> 29:57.127
[ORDERS IN JAPANESE]

30:00.131 --> 30:02.090
Fall in, men.
Don't lag behind.

30:05.845 --> 30:08.055
[MUSIC PAUSES]

30:09.432 --> 30:11.350
[JAPANESE YELLS]

30:24.364 --> 30:27.533
[SOUNDS OF
DIGGING AND HAMMERING]

30:30.703 --> 30:32.746
[FOREBODING MUSIC]

30:58.231 --> 30:59.356
[THUD, YELL]

30:59.524 --> 31:01.108
[THUD]

31:04.028 --> 31:05.737
[MUSIC STOPS]

31:19.878 --> 31:22.546
[ORDERS IN JAPANESE, THEN:]
Attention!

31:24.549 --> 31:27.175
[SHOUTS IN JAPANESE]

31:30.805 --> 31:32.097
You very lucky boys.

31:33.600 --> 31:35.017
You engineers.

31:35.894 --> 31:37.352
You here to help us.

31:38.730 --> 31:40.188
If you help good,

31:40.481 --> 31:42.691
you will have a good war here,

31:43.318 --> 31:44.943
in this good place.

31:45.570 --> 31:46.987
If you don't help us,

31:47.614 --> 31:49.740
you will go back up the line.

31:51.075 --> 31:53.535
Up the line is not a good place.

31:54.871 --> 31:57.289
Now one by one do number,
please.

31:57.373 --> 31:58.665
[YELLS IN JAPANESE]

31:58.791 --> 32:00.042
One.
Two.

32:00.126 --> 32:01.209
Three.
Four.

32:01.294 --> 32:02.294
Five.
Six.

32:02.378 --> 32:03.462
Seven.
Eight.

32:03.546 --> 32:04.838
Nine.
Ten.

32:07.216 --> 32:08.342
Eleven.

32:09.302 --> 32:10.302
Twelve.

32:10.803 --> 32:12.054
Thirteen.
Fourteen.

32:12.138 --> 32:13.805
Fifteen.
Who surrendered?

32:14.390 --> 32:16.516
I never surrendered.

32:16.684 --> 32:18.810
We should still be out there
fighting, now.

32:18.895 --> 32:21.730
We're not fighting, are we?
We're working for the Japanese.

32:21.814 --> 32:24.608
I'm not working
for the bloody Japanese.

32:25.318 --> 32:26.985
We should get out of here.

32:27.195 --> 32:28.362
Organise.

32:28.780 --> 32:29.780
Fight back.

32:30.031 --> 32:31.073
Escape?

32:31.157 --> 32:32.699
There's more of us than them.

32:33.660 --> 32:35.285
We could stroll out.

32:35.620 --> 32:37.704
All of us.
Calm down, Thorlby.

32:38.039 --> 32:40.082
It's easy enough to walk out.

32:40.875 --> 32:42.000
Then what?

32:43.002 --> 32:44.378
Where would you go?

32:45.296 --> 32:47.214
Well we must be somewhere.

32:48.383 --> 32:50.550
We haven't fallen off
the edge of the world.

32:50.635 --> 32:52.135
Er... sir?

32:54.180 --> 32:55.681
Why don't you sit here?

32:56.224 --> 32:58.016
Well I counted four days,

32:58.101 --> 33:00.978
north, from Singapore up
towards Bangkok,

33:01.688 --> 33:04.314
which would put us
somewhere about here.

33:06.192 --> 33:07.484
Then we turned west.

33:10.154 --> 33:11.238
So?

33:13.157 --> 33:16.034
Well there is no railway line
west of Bangkok.

33:16.411 --> 33:18.662
At least there wasn't
before the war.

33:19.122 --> 33:21.081
How do you know, Lomax?

33:21.290 --> 33:23.166
Well you see, the British...

33:24.106 --> 33:26.146
they thought about building
a railway that would run

33:26.170 --> 33:29.423
all the way from where we are
here in Thailand into Burma.

33:29.507 --> 33:33.218
It would complete a line running
all the way from China to India.

33:33.511 --> 33:35.971
If they'd managed it, it would
have taken its place alongside

33:36.055 --> 33:38.223
the great railway journeys
of the world.

33:39.767 --> 33:41.018
Canadian Pacific.

33:41.185 --> 33:42.853
Trans-Siberian.
The Orient Express.

33:42.937 --> 33:44.146
Yeah?

33:44.313 --> 33:45.814
Well why didn't they build it?

33:49.193 --> 33:50.193
Well...

33:53.906 --> 33:55.365
building a railway,

33:55.491 --> 33:57.993
is a hard, miserable job.

33:59.704 --> 34:02.456
It's usually done by poor
immigrant workers.

34:03.875 --> 34:07.836
The great American railways
were built by Chinese peasants.

34:08.755 --> 34:10.630
And even the British railways,

34:10.757 --> 34:14.176
they were built by Irish navvies
fleeing from famine.

34:16.094 --> 34:17.304
But sometimes,

34:18.264 --> 34:21.808
a railway is simply too
difficult to build.

34:27.690 --> 34:31.610
Well it's
hundred of miles to Burma...

34:31.694 --> 34:33.945
through mountains and jungle.

34:36.199 --> 34:37.574
The British decided,

34:38.534 --> 34:40.202
that to build such a railway,

34:40.286 --> 34:42.996
it would be an act not
of engineering,

34:43.664 --> 34:45.415
but of extreme barbarity...

34:46.375 --> 34:47.708
and cruelty.

34:49.545 --> 34:51.880
The conditions would be
such that...

34:52.380 --> 34:53.840
those who did not die,

34:55.426 --> 34:57.552
might well wish that they had.

35:00.098 --> 35:03.892
To build such a railway you would need
more than just poor immigrants.

35:04.602 --> 35:06.228
You'd need an army...

35:07.730 --> 35:09.022
of slaves.

35:11.234 --> 35:12.901
And we've just become that army.

35:12.985 --> 35:14.319
We are not slaves.

35:14.445 --> 35:17.114
We are soldiers.
You remember that.

35:18.449 --> 35:22.577
And we are going to do our best for
those poor bastards up the line.

35:23.955 --> 35:25.872
Lomax, Withins,

35:27.458 --> 35:29.292
how are we fixed for a radio?

35:29.502 --> 35:31.503
[MODERATE
INTRUMENTAL MUSIC]

35:40.596 --> 35:41.596
Lomax.

35:58.739 --> 35:59.823
[IN JAPANESE]

36:00.491 --> 36:01.867
That should be the one.

36:02.368 --> 36:03.451
There we go.

36:11.627 --> 36:12.711
There it is.

36:18.968 --> 36:20.093
Did you get it?

36:20.261 --> 36:21.261
Here.

36:24.140 --> 36:25.307
That's good.

36:25.391 --> 36:27.976
We need a battery, but, Lomax...

36:28.811 --> 36:30.312
what else do we need?

36:31.230 --> 36:33.023
Well I can work on an aerial.

36:33.107 --> 36:35.233
But we must have the capacitor.

36:36.068 --> 36:37.068
Who got that?

36:37.361 --> 36:38.820
Jackson, I think.

36:43.618 --> 36:45.202
But he's up the line.

36:46.662 --> 36:47.829
Oh, great.

37:11.896 --> 37:12.896
Major?

37:13.648 --> 37:15.273
[METAL CLINKS]

37:17.818 --> 37:19.027
Major York?

37:28.996 --> 37:30.080
It's Lomax, sir.

37:30.581 --> 37:31.581
Signals.

37:37.088 --> 37:38.171
[THUD]

37:41.300 --> 37:42.550
[WHIMPERS]

37:54.105 --> 37:56.106
[GROANS]

37:56.190 --> 37:57.315
What's the problem?

37:57.775 --> 37:59.234
She's knackered, mate.

37:59.402 --> 38:00.902
Just like the rest of us.

38:19.005 --> 38:20.005
Jackson...

38:31.559 --> 38:33.768
[ENGINE CHUGS]

38:34.061 --> 38:35.061
[HISS]

38:37.273 --> 38:39.941
[JAPANESE SOLDIERS SHOUT]

38:55.624 --> 38:58.543
It's, um, very beautiful.

38:58.919 --> 39:00.045
What's it called?

39:01.172 --> 39:02.339
The river?

39:02.423 --> 39:03.423
[MUSIC STOPS]

39:03.507 --> 39:05.467
Ah... Maenam Kwae Yai.

39:06.302 --> 39:07.802
Maenam Kwae Yai?

39:07.970 --> 39:09.471
Maenam Kwae Yai.

39:09.597 --> 39:10.680
Thank you.

39:25.613 --> 39:26.821
Maenam Kwae Yai.

39:28.366 --> 39:29.491
Maenam Kwai Yai.

39:30.284 --> 39:32.369
[CRICKETS CHIRP]

39:51.472 --> 39:53.807
[FOREBODING MUSIC]

40:26.882 --> 40:28.883
[STARTER TURNING ENGINE]

40:37.601 --> 40:39.978
[SOLDIER IN JAPANESE]

40:44.400 --> 40:47.193
No good. Yeah.
[SOLDIER IN JAPANESE]

40:47.278 --> 40:48.486
[TURNS ON STARTER]

40:52.992 --> 40:55.452
[MUSIC BUILDS UP]

41:04.336 --> 41:05.628
[MUSIC STOPS]

41:05.754 --> 41:06.838
[CRACKLE]

41:13.596 --> 41:14.596
Ready?

41:15.598 --> 41:17.348
What if Hitler's in London?

41:18.225 --> 41:19.726
What do we tell the men?

41:21.353 --> 41:23.563
I can't say it sounds very likely.

41:38.954 --> 41:39.954
It's running!

41:39.997 --> 41:41.456
[STATIC]

41:48.923 --> 41:50.798
[TUNING]

41:54.720 --> 41:55.929
[MUSIC OVER RADIO]

41:56.013 --> 41:57.472
It's working.

42:14.490 --> 42:17.575
[ANNOUNCER:] This is the BBC
Home and Forces program.

42:17.660 --> 42:19.536
This is Bruce Belfidge.

42:19.870 --> 42:22.330
The Axis forces
in the Western Desert

42:22.414 --> 42:24.415
after twelve days and nights

42:24.542 --> 42:27.752
of ceaseless attacks
by our land and air forces

42:27.878 --> 42:30.004
are now in full retreat.

42:30.673 --> 42:33.299
Their disordered columns
are being relentlessly attacked

42:33.384 --> 42:38.346
by our land forces and by the
Allied air forces by day and night.

42:40.558 --> 42:42.600
In the morning
there was a rumour

42:42.685 --> 42:45.562
that German tanks were
just over the hill.

42:45.896 --> 42:48.314
Armed patrols went
out on the road.

42:48.607 --> 42:50.650
Trees were felled at roadblocks

42:51.026 --> 42:56.155
and thunderbolts and lightning appeared
low over the town and began weaving...

42:56.240 --> 42:57.824
[ANNOUNCER'S VOICE FADES]

43:00.035 --> 43:03.705
[ANNOUNCER:] What we
have done is rekindle a fire

43:04.039 --> 43:05.623
in British hearts

43:06.041 --> 43:08.293
here and all over the world

43:09.003 --> 43:10.336
which will glow...

43:10.421 --> 43:12.880
[ANNOUNCER'S VOICE
SLOWLY FADES]

43:22.641 --> 43:24.601
Major... Major York.

43:24.727 --> 43:27.228
The Russians have
retaken Stalingrad.

43:30.941 --> 43:32.442
Got them on the run, sir.

43:36.196 --> 43:37.196
Sir?

43:37.990 --> 43:38.990
Come on, sir.

43:40.367 --> 43:42.201
We've got Hitler on the run.

43:45.539 --> 43:46.748
That's it, sir.

43:46.999 --> 43:49.542
And we're bombing Germany
24 hours a day,

43:49.918 --> 43:52.545
now the US Air Force
has joined in.

43:53.172 --> 43:55.048
[JAPANESE SOLDIER SHOUTS]

43:55.883 --> 43:57.592
The men, sir, right?

43:58.135 --> 44:00.303
You've got to let them
know it's going our way.

44:01.305 --> 44:02.972
[SHOUTS IN JAPANESE]

44:22.618 --> 44:24.369
We've got Hitler on the run.

44:24.453 --> 44:25.453
Pass it round.

44:27.414 --> 44:29.666
The Russians have taken Stalingrad.

44:29.750 --> 44:30.958
Be careful.

44:32.628 --> 44:36.673
[ANNOUNCER:]... went on fighting
until they had little ammunition left.

44:36.840 --> 44:39.425
Our troops in the north
put down a smokescreen

44:39.635 --> 44:41.552
and under cover
they withdrew a little

44:41.637 --> 44:44.305
while our bombers went in
in three deadly waves

44:44.431 --> 44:46.933
to deliver a large aerial
bombardment and one

44:47.017 --> 44:49.060
of the heaviest
of the whole campaign.

44:49.186 --> 44:52.647
They rang the church bells at home for the
first time since the beginning of the war.

44:56.985 --> 44:58.820
[DISTANT CHIMES]

45:06.078 --> 45:07.328
[BELL ALARM]

45:08.414 --> 45:10.289
[ORDERS IN JAPANESE]

45:13.001 --> 45:14.961
[FOREBODING MUSIC]

45:31.979 --> 45:34.188
[SHOUTS IN JAPANESE]

45:42.948 --> 45:46.576
[EXCHANGE OF ORDERS
IN JAPANESE]

45:49.830 --> 45:57.830
[ORDERS IN JAPANESE]

46:09.933 --> 46:12.935
[YELLS IN JAPANESE]

46:13.187 --> 46:14.687
[PANTS]

46:21.153 --> 46:22.737
[JAPANESE OFFICER YELLS]

46:23.530 --> 46:24.697
[YELLS IN JAPANESE]

46:24.782 --> 46:26.282
[MUSIC STOPS]

46:44.384 --> 46:46.344
[JAPANESE OFFICER SHOUTS]

46:49.014 --> 46:50.556
[ORDERS IN JAPANESE]

46:53.894 --> 46:55.061
Thorlby.

46:57.815 --> 46:58.815
Finlay.

47:01.985 --> 47:02.985
Withins.

47:06.323 --> 47:07.323
Lomax.

47:08.909 --> 47:09.909
Lomax!!!

47:10.202 --> 47:12.328
[TRUCK ENGINE ROARS]

47:19.545 --> 47:20.795
[ENGINE STOPS]

47:23.757 --> 47:24.924
[YELLS IN JAPANESE]

47:34.434 --> 47:35.893
Soldier.

47:53.120 --> 47:54.745
[THUD, GROAN]

47:56.707 --> 47:57.832
[WITHINS COUGHS]

47:57.916 --> 48:00.209
[WITHINS SCREAMS, MOANS]

48:01.795 --> 48:03.504
[WITHINS SCREAMS]

48:05.299 --> 48:07.800
[WITHINS GROANS,
THEN COUGHS]

48:09.303 --> 48:12.555
[BEATINGS, GROANS
AND SCREAMS CONTINUE]

48:36.163 --> 48:38.706
[SLOW MUSIC]

49:02.397 --> 49:05.483
I think it was the bravest thing
I've ever seen.

49:25.629 --> 49:27.713
[MUSIC BUILDS UP,
NO OTHER SOUNDS]

50:09.006 --> 50:10.715
[MUSIC SLOWS DOWN]

50:13.593 --> 50:17.304
[ROGERS:] Though I walk through
the valley of the shadow of death,

50:17.347 --> 50:18.973
I will fear no evil.

50:19.599 --> 50:21.267
For thou art with me.

50:22.936 --> 50:26.022
Thy rod and thy staff,
they comfort me.

50:27.941 --> 50:32.153
Thou prepares the table for me
in the presence of my enemies.

50:34.322 --> 50:36.240
Surely goodness and...

50:36.491 --> 50:37.950
[SIGHS]

50:40.579 --> 50:43.748
mercy will follow me
for the rest of my life.

50:44.958 --> 50:47.001
[MUSIC BUILDS UP]

50:47.252 --> 50:49.086
[JAPANESE SOLDIER GROWLS]

51:01.975 --> 51:03.559
[MUSIC SLOWS DOWN]

51:04.144 --> 51:05.519
It was...

51:06.855 --> 51:07.855
madness.

51:15.572 --> 51:17.073
[SIGHS]

51:20.702 --> 51:22.453
But you can talk about it.

51:24.998 --> 51:27.083
Why can't he talk to me about it?

51:28.126 --> 51:30.002
[MUSIC STOPS]

51:36.468 --> 51:39.386
I told you, you couldn't possibly
imagine what he's been through.

51:39.638 --> 51:42.098
What did I say?
What? Please, please.

51:43.308 --> 51:44.892
Please don't shut me out.

51:47.687 --> 51:48.938
Please.

52:02.202 --> 52:04.537
[WHEEZES]

52:06.581 --> 52:08.707
[FINLAY:]
We had him for a little while.

52:08.875 --> 52:10.084
A week or so.

52:11.545 --> 52:13.963
We did our best to put him
back together again.

52:23.682 --> 52:25.766
But we knew it wasn't over.

52:30.605 --> 52:31.981
They came for him.

52:32.941 --> 52:34.275
The young officer.

52:34.734 --> 52:35.985
Kempeitai.

52:36.486 --> 52:37.987
Their secret police.

52:39.197 --> 52:41.240
Lomax. We are satisfied
you are guilty.

52:42.409 --> 52:44.326
You will be killed shortly,

52:44.828 --> 52:48.122
but it will be to your advantage
to tell me the truth.

52:50.041 --> 52:52.585
[ORDERS IN JAPANESE]

52:53.086 --> 52:54.378
Raise your arms.

52:55.088 --> 52:56.672
You will come with me.

53:00.886 --> 53:03.304
[FAST PACED MUSIC,
MOTORBIKE ENGINE]

53:19.654 --> 53:21.280
[MUSIC STOPS]

53:21.531 --> 53:24.241
And then we didn't see him
for two weeks.

53:28.246 --> 53:29.663
[SIGHS]

53:31.583 --> 53:33.751
[JAPANESE SOLDIERS GROAN]

53:45.486 --> 53:47.366
[FINLAY:] He never told me
what they did to him.

53:47.390 --> 53:49.058
[SLOW MUSIC]

53:51.561 --> 53:53.270
[TRUCK ENGINE STARTS]

54:00.111 --> 54:02.613
There are some things,
Patti, that are so bad,

54:02.697 --> 54:04.573
so humiliating and...

54:06.076 --> 54:07.826
shameful...

54:09.246 --> 54:11.163
I'm not sure you could ever
talk about them.

54:12.290 --> 54:14.750
Especially not
to someone you love.

54:16.419 --> 54:17.920
Or want to love.

54:21.424 --> 54:22.424
I have to try.

54:33.937 --> 54:35.479
[SLOW MUSIC]

54:59.379 --> 55:01.005
[RADIO TUNING]

55:03.174 --> 55:05.592
[SLOW CLASSICAL MUSIC
FROM THE RADIO]

55:15.186 --> 55:16.186
Patti.

55:53.641 --> 55:58.771
Eric.

56:01.649 --> 56:02.858
[TURNS OFF RADIO]

56:09.115 --> 56:10.741
[DOOR SLAMS]

56:19.459 --> 56:22.878
I hope you're not planning
to throw yourself in there.

56:23.922 --> 56:27.174
As a gentleman I'd feel obliged
to go in after you,

56:28.510 --> 56:30.969
and that may well be
the end of me.

56:40.980 --> 56:43.857
The men used to call me Uncle.

56:46.194 --> 56:48.278
They thought
I'd look after them,

56:48.446 --> 56:50.030
and I did, while we were there.

56:51.366 --> 56:52.449
But here...

56:52.534 --> 56:54.326
every month
I stare into those...

56:54.953 --> 56:56.829
bitter, half-awake faces,

56:57.288 --> 57:01.708
and I know they desperately need me
to put them back together again.

57:06.297 --> 57:07.339
But I can't.

57:09.759 --> 57:12.094
There's nothing
I can do for them now.

57:13.972 --> 57:16.223
I think you do more
than you know.

57:17.934 --> 57:20.102
Eric did something wonderful.

57:20.687 --> 57:22.479
He stuck his neck out

57:22.814 --> 57:26.024
to give us hope in a nightmare
5,000 miles from home.

57:27.110 --> 57:28.527
He should have...

57:29.320 --> 57:30.863
medals and glory.

57:31.823 --> 57:33.907
Can't you make him
understand that?

57:35.326 --> 57:36.493
No.

57:37.454 --> 57:38.579
It's too late.

57:40.081 --> 57:43.876
The only time I've seen him light up
was when you came along.

57:50.550 --> 57:51.842
Patti...

57:56.347 --> 57:57.764
I have something.

57:59.934 --> 58:01.477
I think it's the most

58:01.728 --> 58:04.563
dangerous thing I've
ever held in my hand.

58:05.231 --> 58:06.690
You must decide...

58:07.150 --> 58:08.734
if Eric should see it.

58:16.743 --> 58:17.993
It's him.

58:18.536 --> 58:20.579
The young Kempeitai officer.

58:21.539 --> 58:23.040
And he's alive.

58:24.584 --> 58:26.001
Nagase.

58:27.212 --> 58:29.004
I don't know what he will do...

58:29.130 --> 58:30.130
if we tell him.

58:33.718 --> 58:35.886
But doesn't Eric
deserve a chance...

58:37.013 --> 58:38.430
for justice?

58:41.226 --> 58:42.726
Will you stand by him?

58:45.188 --> 58:46.563
Whatever he does?

58:54.030 --> 58:56.323
[SLOW MUSIC]

58:59.744 --> 59:00.994
Whatever he does.

59:12.298 --> 59:13.340
I want to.

59:16.010 --> 59:19.471
I can't imagine anything worse
than where he is now.

59:48.209 --> 59:49.626
[THUD]

59:53.298 --> 59:55.048
It's him, isn't it?

59:58.553 --> 01:00:00.554
The bastard's back in Kanburi.

01:00:00.638 --> 01:00:02.639
Back at the scene of the crime.

01:00:02.807 --> 01:00:04.308
Can you believe that?

01:00:06.978 --> 01:00:08.145
He's alive?

01:00:08.354 --> 01:00:09.938
And he's living off it!

01:00:10.440 --> 01:00:12.566
Showing the railway to tourists.

01:00:13.901 --> 01:00:16.653
Bridge on the bloody
River Kwai holidays.

01:00:18.323 --> 01:00:19.823
Nagase.

01:00:20.867 --> 01:00:22.701
I've had it translated.

01:00:29.250 --> 01:00:32.711
[HEART BEAT STARTS TO RACE,
THEN SLOWS DOWN]

01:00:39.385 --> 01:00:40.677
Look him up.

01:00:41.804 --> 01:00:44.056
He won't have a clue
you're coming.

01:00:44.766 --> 01:00:46.516
Element of surprise, Eric.

01:00:46.726 --> 01:00:48.143
Always good.

01:00:54.817 --> 01:00:56.234
The years I've spent,

01:00:59.364 --> 01:01:01.114
imagining I'd found him.

01:01:02.492 --> 01:01:03.659
Making him beg.

01:01:05.912 --> 01:01:07.245
Making him scream.

01:01:10.750 --> 01:01:13.752
I've nursed myself to
sleep on those sounds.

01:01:17.840 --> 01:01:21.218
And the snapping of the hyoid bone,
and the chopstick through the eye.

01:01:32.730 --> 01:01:34.064
Your timing's off.

01:01:36.317 --> 01:01:37.442
What do you mean?

01:01:44.117 --> 01:01:46.618
We're not soldiers anymore, Uncle.

01:01:47.537 --> 01:01:49.913
We're bank clerks,
school teachers,

01:01:51.040 --> 01:01:53.041
engineers, retired persons.

01:01:56.921 --> 01:02:00.924
If you'd come to me with this a year
ago, I'd have hunted him down.

01:02:04.178 --> 01:02:05.762
But now I'm a husband.

01:02:08.474 --> 01:02:10.475
And she means everything to me.

01:02:14.355 --> 01:02:17.023
No husband would treat her
the way you do.

01:02:20.111 --> 01:02:21.111
You punish her.

01:02:21.195 --> 01:02:22.404
You punish her!

01:02:25.658 --> 01:02:29.077
When we surrendered,
the Japs said we weren't men.

01:02:29.245 --> 01:02:32.372
Real men would kill themselves.

01:02:33.458 --> 01:02:34.833
Would die of shame.

01:02:34.917 --> 01:02:35.959
But we said no.

01:02:36.210 --> 01:02:38.420
We'll live to fight you.

01:02:39.213 --> 01:02:41.089
We'll live for revenge.

01:02:42.800 --> 01:02:44.092
But we didn't, no.

01:02:44.761 --> 01:02:46.052
We don't live.

01:02:47.305 --> 01:02:49.264
We're miming in the choir.

01:02:49.515 --> 01:02:50.724
We can't love.

01:02:50.808 --> 01:02:51.850
We can't sleep.

01:02:53.853 --> 01:02:55.937
We're an army of ghosts.

01:03:02.737 --> 01:03:04.529
What happened in that room?

01:03:07.533 --> 01:03:09.117
What did they do to you?

01:03:14.123 --> 01:03:15.957
I think you should go now.

01:03:18.127 --> 01:03:19.586
Don't waste this.

01:03:19.962 --> 01:03:22.380
At least one of us
deserves some peace.

01:03:23.049 --> 01:03:25.342
It's too late for me
and the other guys but...

01:03:25.426 --> 01:03:28.720
you were the strongest.
You were the best of us.

01:03:30.014 --> 01:03:31.431
You do this for me.

01:03:32.725 --> 01:03:34.476
[SLOW MUSIC]

01:03:40.233 --> 01:03:41.358
Please.

01:03:45.613 --> 01:03:48.365
Come on. We're walking
Finlay to the station.

01:03:49.158 --> 01:03:51.576
You... you want me
to come with you?

01:03:52.328 --> 01:03:55.622
I thought we'd take him along
the front, give him a little tour.

01:04:03.840 --> 01:04:05.549
I'm not a train spotter.

01:04:06.092 --> 01:04:07.801
I'm a railway enthusiast.

01:04:08.553 --> 01:04:10.595
You know we met on a train.

01:04:11.055 --> 01:04:13.932
You can't just say "a train"
when you're talking about Eric.

01:04:14.016 --> 01:04:16.393
You have to say which train,
when it was built

01:04:16.477 --> 01:04:19.145
where it was stopping,
how many wheels it had.

01:04:22.775 --> 01:04:23.859
[MUSIC STOPS]

01:04:24.235 --> 01:04:25.694
[PATTI CHUCKLES]

01:04:28.990 --> 01:04:31.533
I'm going to send him a message.

01:04:32.827 --> 01:04:34.870
Something he won't
be able to ignore.

01:04:36.581 --> 01:04:37.956
[STATION MASTER WHISTLES]

01:04:43.921 --> 01:04:45.755
[SLOW MUSIC]

01:04:51.095 --> 01:04:55.015
[TRAIN SIREN SOUNDS OFF,
DIESEL ENGINE INTENSIFIES]

01:05:20.041 --> 01:05:22.167
[PHONE RINGS]

01:05:25.588 --> 01:05:26.713
Yes?

01:05:30.843 --> 01:05:32.969
[ROPE STRAINS,
FINLAY GURGLES]

01:05:36.349 --> 01:05:37.599
Oh, my God.

01:05:39.310 --> 01:05:41.311
Alright, thank you.

01:05:45.858 --> 01:05:47.525
[PATTI HANGS UP]

01:05:59.747 --> 01:06:00.956
It's Finlay...

01:06:04.961 --> 01:06:05.961
Where?

01:06:07.880 --> 01:06:10.757
Er... Warminster.

01:06:13.703 --> 01:06:15.864
He must have caught
the Birmingham train, changed at...

01:06:15.888 --> 01:06:18.098
[WHISPERS:]
Stop it. Stop it!

01:06:21.727 --> 01:06:24.396
This is what you're
going to do, isn't it?

01:06:27.108 --> 01:06:28.692
Isn't that what you want?

01:06:30.569 --> 01:06:32.320
I've seen you with him.

01:06:32.613 --> 01:06:34.572
Your secret little chats.

01:06:36.242 --> 01:06:38.868
That's what happens
when you start interfering.

01:06:40.413 --> 01:06:41.746
Hope you're happy.

01:06:57.430 --> 01:06:59.014
[DOOR SLAMS]

01:07:01.892 --> 01:07:04.394
[PRIEST:]
May he have peace with God
through our Lord,

01:07:04.478 --> 01:07:07.647
Jesus Christ, and rejoice in
the hope of the Glory of God

01:07:07.773 --> 01:07:11.609
and not only so, but
we glory in tribulations also

01:07:11.694 --> 01:07:13.570
knowing that tribulation

01:07:13.696 --> 01:07:14.863
worketh patience

01:07:15.364 --> 01:07:17.365
and patience, experience

01:07:17.700 --> 01:07:21.286
and experience, hope...
[PRIEST'S VOICE FADES]

01:07:38.971 --> 01:07:40.180
One.

01:07:40.723 --> 01:07:41.723
Two.

01:07:41.849 --> 01:07:42.849
Three.

01:07:42.933 --> 01:07:44.517
Four.
Five.

01:07:45.227 --> 01:07:46.644
Six.

01:07:46.896 --> 01:07:48.021
Seven.

01:07:48.230 --> 01:07:49.397
Eight.

01:07:49.732 --> 01:07:50.940
Nine.

01:07:51.192 --> 01:07:52.192
Ten.

01:07:53.944 --> 01:07:55.111
Jack.

01:07:55.654 --> 01:07:56.654
Queen.

01:07:57.823 --> 01:07:59.449
King.

01:08:20.888 --> 01:08:23.348
[MUSIC BUILDS UP]

01:09:01.345 --> 01:09:03.470
[MUSIC SLOWS DOWN]

01:10:15.711 --> 01:10:17.378
[MUSIC STOPS]

01:10:23.802 --> 01:10:25.261
[KNIFE SLITHES]

01:10:52.414 --> 01:10:55.875
[NAGASE TO TOURISTS:]
The flowers are an offering
for the Mother of Waters.

01:10:56.377 --> 01:10:59.254
They symbolise the desire
to atone for any evil

01:10:59.338 --> 01:11:01.547
that the pilgrim has done in life.

01:11:02.049 --> 01:11:04.759
[TOURIST:] I thought all
the Buddhas were fat and jolly.

01:11:04.927 --> 01:11:07.929
[NAGASE:] No. The fat Buddha
is not this Buddha.

01:11:08.347 --> 01:11:11.474
This Buddha is
Siddhartha Guatama.

01:11:12.101 --> 01:11:14.769
The great Buddha, the Founder.

01:11:17.898 --> 01:11:19.732
The fat one is a monk.

01:11:20.025 --> 01:11:21.526
He is called Putai.

01:11:22.569 --> 01:11:24.445
Buddha is not a name.

01:11:25.489 --> 01:11:29.617
It is a title, like your saint,
perhaps.

01:11:32.538 --> 01:11:34.205
Come this way, please.

01:11:35.624 --> 01:11:37.292
I am from Japan.

01:11:37.501 --> 01:11:40.169
I come to this place
on a pilgrimage.

01:11:40.462 --> 01:11:42.922
This is my 57th pilgrimage.

01:11:48.762 --> 01:11:52.890
This area was occupied
by my country during the war.

01:11:52.975 --> 01:11:55.101
[OMINOUS MUSIC]

01:12:03.110 --> 01:12:05.361
[MUSICAL STRESS]

01:12:15.414 --> 01:12:18.541
We are going to the War Museum
over in Kempeitai.

01:12:35.476 --> 01:12:36.976
Thanks for coming.

01:12:38.062 --> 01:12:39.145
See you.

01:12:39.396 --> 01:12:40.772
Thank you, please.

01:13:04.546 --> 01:13:07.298
[DOOR SQUEAKS]

01:13:11.678 --> 01:13:13.429
[MUSIC STOPS]

01:13:36.286 --> 01:13:37.495
Sir.

01:13:38.539 --> 01:13:40.706
I'm afraid the museum is closed.

01:13:43.377 --> 01:13:45.336
I've come a very long way.

01:13:48.424 --> 01:13:52.301
I have a particular interest in
knowing what happened here.

01:13:57.182 --> 01:13:59.183
What happened to these men?

01:14:00.477 --> 01:14:03.020
It will be open again
tomorrow morning.

01:14:03.105 --> 01:14:05.148
Perhaps you could return then?

01:14:08.402 --> 01:14:11.028
I'm afraid this won't
keep till tomorrow.

01:14:15.284 --> 01:14:17.827
I'm surprised
you don't recognise me.

01:14:22.916 --> 01:14:24.333
Sit down, Mr Nagase.

01:14:49.860 --> 01:14:51.694
Mister...

01:14:52.029 --> 01:14:53.905
Lomax.

01:14:57.784 --> 01:15:00.703
We won't be needing
an interpreter this time.

01:15:02.998 --> 01:15:06.375
Of course, that wasn't your
real function last time, was it?

01:15:09.421 --> 01:15:11.380
You will be killed shortly.

01:15:13.926 --> 01:15:17.470
But it will be to your advantage
to answer my questions in the meantime.

01:15:19.806 --> 01:15:21.933
How can it be to my advantage?

01:15:24.186 --> 01:15:27.813
Your friends have already
admitted to building a radio...

01:15:28.148 --> 01:15:30.608
in order to conspire
with our enemy.

01:15:31.944 --> 01:15:35.530
They also said that you're
the ringleader of the plot.

01:15:40.911 --> 01:15:42.954
He can do a lot worse...

01:15:43.455 --> 01:15:44.830
than to kill you.

01:15:45.040 --> 01:15:46.791
[OFFICER IN JAPANESE]

01:15:50.796 --> 01:15:53.005
We want to know about the map.

01:15:53.966 --> 01:15:55.466
Why did you draw a map?

01:15:57.427 --> 01:16:00.721
Well it's a map of the railway.
He knows that.

01:16:00.806 --> 01:16:02.181
Who's it for?

01:16:04.893 --> 01:16:06.852
For me. It's the railway.

01:16:06.937 --> 01:16:09.105
We know it is the railway.

01:16:09.856 --> 01:16:12.275
Why did you draw
a map of the railway?

01:16:15.195 --> 01:16:17.071
I'm a railway enthusiast.

01:16:18.031 --> 01:16:19.532
Enthusiast?

01:16:21.910 --> 01:16:23.119
I like trains.

01:16:24.746 --> 01:16:26.205
I really like trains.

01:16:29.918 --> 01:16:32.461
You used this
to communicate with

01:16:32.546 --> 01:16:35.798
Thai Resistance
and their Chinese paymasters.

01:16:36.425 --> 01:16:38.342
No, I didn't.

01:16:39.428 --> 01:16:40.886
How could I do that?

01:16:41.513 --> 01:16:45.558
You received information and then
passed it on to them with this.

01:16:47.102 --> 01:16:48.519
How could I do that?

01:16:49.938 --> 01:16:51.606
I am asking the questions.

01:16:51.690 --> 01:16:53.316
You must answer them.

01:16:53.525 --> 01:16:56.068
But it's a receiver.

01:16:56.570 --> 01:16:58.154
It receives signals.

01:16:58.989 --> 01:17:00.656
It doesn't transmit them.

01:17:00.907 --> 01:17:03.034
How can you transmit
with a receiver?

01:17:03.118 --> 01:17:07.538
You built this transmitter to tell
the Chinese about our railway!

01:17:14.963 --> 01:17:16.088
So...

01:17:18.383 --> 01:17:20.259
Which bit do you talk into?

01:17:23.096 --> 01:17:26.724
Well if it's a transmitter
you need to talk into it. Where?

01:17:33.774 --> 01:17:35.608
You do not ask questions.

01:17:36.443 --> 01:17:37.943
I ask questions.

01:17:38.278 --> 01:17:39.987
You answer the questions.

01:17:40.405 --> 01:17:42.406
I'm just trying to help you.

01:17:44.201 --> 01:17:46.702
[TALKS IN JAPANESE]

01:17:46.787 --> 01:17:49.038
[REPLIES IN JAPANESE]

01:17:50.540 --> 01:17:52.708
[SHOUTS IN JAPANESE]

01:17:52.793 --> 01:17:54.502
[FOREBODING MUSIC]

01:17:58.423 --> 01:18:00.257
[SOLDIER ORDERS IN JAPANESE]

01:18:29.306 --> 01:18:30.306
Thank you.

01:18:30.330 --> 01:18:31.914
[OFFICER SHOUTS IN JAPANESE]

01:18:43.093 --> 01:18:44.760
Just tell them.

01:18:46.054 --> 01:18:48.431
Or they will make you tell them.

01:18:48.682 --> 01:18:52.560
First personal singular,
not third person plural. You...

01:18:53.520 --> 01:18:55.646
tortured me, you see,
not they. You.

01:18:58.734 --> 01:19:01.068
They were afraid you were...

01:19:01.153 --> 01:19:04.488
No, you is second person.
You need the first person.

01:19:04.698 --> 01:19:07.074
I tortured you,

01:19:08.326 --> 01:19:09.535
Lieutenant Lomax.

01:19:09.619 --> 01:19:10.661
Try it. I...

01:19:10.746 --> 01:19:13.122
I am at a loss.

01:19:14.750 --> 01:19:17.710
I want to ask...
No, no, you don't ask. I ask.

01:19:17.794 --> 01:19:20.796
I ask the questions.
You answer.

01:19:21.506 --> 01:19:23.090
Why did you build the radio?

01:19:23.175 --> 01:19:25.217
Who helped you
to build the radio?

01:19:25.302 --> 01:19:26.427
No one.

01:19:27.262 --> 01:19:28.763
No one helped us.

01:19:30.015 --> 01:19:32.057
We built it ourselves.
Liar.

01:19:32.142 --> 01:19:33.434
You tell lies.

01:19:33.602 --> 01:19:35.519
Why did you build the radio?!

01:19:39.274 --> 01:19:40.441
To...

01:19:42.277 --> 01:19:43.360
To listen to.

01:19:44.988 --> 01:19:46.280
To hear voices.

01:19:47.282 --> 01:19:48.949
To know what was
happening at home.

01:19:49.910 --> 01:19:51.202
[SMASH, GROAN]

01:19:51.411 --> 01:19:54.705
[SPEAKS JAPANESE
IN LOW THREATENING VOICE]

01:20:04.049 --> 01:20:05.800
At the beginning of time

01:20:07.093 --> 01:20:08.677
the clock struck one.

01:20:11.056 --> 01:20:12.515
Then dropped the dew

01:20:13.558 --> 01:20:15.434
and the clock struck two.

01:20:15.977 --> 01:20:17.645
[THUD, GROAN]

01:20:18.563 --> 01:20:20.648
Who asked you to draw the map?

01:20:22.400 --> 01:20:24.318
From the dew grew a tree

01:20:25.570 --> 01:20:27.321
and the clock struck three.

01:20:27.906 --> 01:20:30.074
Where did you get
the components for the radio?

01:20:30.909 --> 01:20:31.951
[THUD, SCREAM]

01:20:32.452 --> 01:20:34.578
Then the tree made a door

01:20:35.956 --> 01:20:37.665
and the clock struck four.

01:20:41.461 --> 01:20:42.461
No!

01:20:43.713 --> 01:20:45.214
Man came alive

01:20:46.508 --> 01:20:48.217
and the clock struck five.

01:20:48.552 --> 01:20:49.718
[THUD]

01:20:52.180 --> 01:20:53.347
Count not.

01:20:54.850 --> 01:20:55.850
Waste not

01:20:57.185 --> 01:20:59.019
the hours on the clock.

01:21:02.148 --> 01:21:04.108
Behold I stand

01:21:04.901 --> 01:21:06.694
at the door and knock.

01:21:07.612 --> 01:21:11.740
[MUSIC CRESCENDO,
SOLDIER SHOUTS]

01:21:23.670 --> 01:21:25.504
[OFFICER ORDERS]

01:21:26.006 --> 01:21:27.965
[MUSIC STOPS]

01:21:30.719 --> 01:21:33.470
I did not expect you
to be alive.

01:21:34.055 --> 01:21:37.266
No, of course you didn't.
You thought you'd got away with it.

01:21:39.811 --> 01:21:41.270
Why are you alive?

01:21:43.607 --> 01:21:44.899
Why are we alive?

01:21:44.983 --> 01:21:46.400
No, you.

01:21:48.361 --> 01:21:49.486
Why are you alive?

01:21:51.489 --> 01:21:53.741
You were a war criminal.
Why didn't they hang you?

01:21:53.825 --> 01:21:55.784
Not a war criminal.

01:21:56.328 --> 01:21:57.703
Just an interpreter.

01:21:57.787 --> 01:22:00.497
You were Kempeitai,
you knew everything!

01:22:05.712 --> 01:22:07.546
Why did they let you live?

01:22:09.758 --> 01:22:13.093
[BUZZING OF FLIES,
FOREBODING MUSIC]

01:22:31.071 --> 01:22:32.655
[SOLDIER:]
Easy does it.

01:22:32.739 --> 01:22:34.657
[PLANE ENGINES ROAR]

01:22:45.251 --> 01:22:46.752
[THOMPSON:]
Now listen.

01:22:48.254 --> 01:22:50.255
We intend to treat you fairly.

01:22:50.924 --> 01:22:52.883
We are civilised human beings,

01:22:54.386 --> 01:22:56.971
but we do need to see
that justice is done.

01:22:58.431 --> 01:22:59.932
You're going to be transferred

01:23:00.016 --> 01:23:01.809
to Bangkok while we look into
some of the charges

01:23:01.893 --> 01:23:04.645
that have been made
against you.
[SPEAKS IN JAPANESE]

01:23:06.648 --> 01:23:07.648
Translator?

01:23:08.900 --> 01:23:10.025
Yes, sir.

01:23:11.444 --> 01:23:12.444
Kempeitai?

01:23:13.321 --> 01:23:14.405
No, sir.

01:23:15.323 --> 01:23:16.323
Translator.

01:23:16.700 --> 01:23:18.909
Did you work for the Kempeitai?

01:23:19.452 --> 01:23:21.412
Torture? Beatings?

01:23:23.498 --> 01:23:25.207
Only translation.

01:23:30.338 --> 01:23:31.630
Over there.

01:23:39.389 --> 01:23:42.474
[NAGASE:] I worked for
the War Graves Commission.

01:23:44.477 --> 01:23:46.478
They needed interpreters.

01:23:48.898 --> 01:23:50.816
We travelled the railway.

01:23:52.569 --> 01:23:54.486
We find dead bodies.

01:23:56.281 --> 01:23:58.657
[DOLEFUL MUSIC]

01:23:59.409 --> 01:24:01.785
[DIGGING SOUNDS]

01:24:03.621 --> 01:24:05.164
We identified them.

01:24:09.919 --> 01:24:12.671
We brought them here
to be buried properly.

01:24:25.351 --> 01:24:29.229
So you went up the line.
You buried the men you helped to kill.

01:24:32.734 --> 01:24:34.109
That's when I saw...

01:24:37.489 --> 01:24:39.615
so many bodies.
[VOICE TREMBLES]

01:24:41.034 --> 01:24:42.576
So very many.

01:24:45.580 --> 01:24:49.625
I had not imagined
so many had died.

01:24:49.709 --> 01:24:51.210
Murdered.

01:24:52.128 --> 01:24:54.713
The word you're
looking for is murdered.

01:24:56.007 --> 01:24:58.300
So many had been murdered.

01:25:08.978 --> 01:25:09.978
Go on.

01:25:11.356 --> 01:25:12.523
Murdered.

01:25:13.817 --> 01:25:14.900
Yes.

01:25:17.987 --> 01:25:19.404
That's what I saw.

01:25:19.489 --> 01:25:20.823
So many murdered.

01:25:22.158 --> 01:25:24.118
So I will speak.

01:25:27.413 --> 01:25:29.331
I make pilgrimages.

01:25:30.625 --> 01:25:31.917
I work for...

01:25:34.420 --> 01:25:35.921
reconciliation.

01:25:38.424 --> 01:25:40.467
I will not let them forget...

01:25:43.096 --> 01:25:44.513
the tragedy of war.

01:25:44.597 --> 01:25:45.806
The what?

01:25:47.559 --> 01:25:48.767
The tragedy of war.

01:25:48.852 --> 01:25:51.395
No, this wasn't a tragedy.
This was a crime.

01:25:52.689 --> 01:25:53.939
You're not tragic.

01:25:55.817 --> 01:25:57.234
You're a criminal.

01:25:59.112 --> 01:26:03.282
You were an intelligent,
educated man

01:26:04.159 --> 01:26:05.826
and you did nothing.

01:26:06.786 --> 01:26:08.453
You're a criminal and a liar.

01:26:08.830 --> 01:26:10.164
Mr. Lomax...

01:26:11.040 --> 01:26:12.833
Through my work here

01:26:13.001 --> 01:26:15.127
I have found
some peace in my life.

01:26:16.713 --> 01:26:18.088
If I can help you...

01:26:24.929 --> 01:26:27.681
[BREATHES HEAVILY]

01:27:06.596 --> 01:27:08.597
[MUSIC BUILDS UP]

01:27:34.165 --> 01:27:35.499
Mr. Lomax.

01:27:36.668 --> 01:27:40.671
I'm trying to answer these questions
because you are asking them.

01:27:40.880 --> 01:27:44.132
But I don't think these questions
are the right questions!

01:27:45.510 --> 01:27:46.760
[GASPS]

01:28:17.792 --> 01:28:20.502
[RHYTMICALLY ACCENTED MUSIC]

01:28:24.924 --> 01:28:26.800
[WATER TRICKLES]

01:29:37.246 --> 01:29:38.330
[MUSIC STOPS]

01:30:10.446 --> 01:30:12.572
[SLOW MUSIC]

01:30:38.683 --> 01:30:41.268
[WATER TRICKLES]

01:30:47.733 --> 01:30:51.111
[MUFFLED WATERFLOW]

01:30:58.411 --> 01:31:00.454
[SPLASH, GARGLE]

01:31:08.921 --> 01:31:10.255
[CHOKES]

01:31:11.591 --> 01:31:13.300
[COUGHS]

01:31:13.384 --> 01:31:15.010
[ORDERES IN JAPANESE]

01:31:15.178 --> 01:31:16.344
No!

01:31:22.894 --> 01:31:24.644
[CHOKES]

01:31:29.442 --> 01:31:30.942
[SCREAMS]

01:31:38.367 --> 01:31:40.035
[ORDERS IN JAPANESE]

01:31:43.289 --> 01:31:45.123
[SCREAMS]

01:31:50.963 --> 01:31:52.756
[ORDERS IN JAPANESE]

01:31:56.636 --> 01:31:57.636
[COUGHS]

01:31:57.720 --> 01:31:59.471
[OFFICER ORDERS
IN JAPANESE]

01:32:02.183 --> 01:32:03.600
[CHOKES]

01:32:07.480 --> 01:32:09.189
[SCREAMS]

01:32:10.775 --> 01:32:14.611
Mother! Mother! Mother!

01:32:16.197 --> 01:32:19.199
Why won't you help me?
Mother!

01:32:19.992 --> 01:32:23.286
Mother!

01:32:40.179 --> 01:32:41.346
Alright!

01:32:41.681 --> 01:32:44.015
Alright, I'll tell you! I'll tell you.

01:32:44.642 --> 01:32:46.434
I'll tell you, I'll tell you.
I'll tell you.

01:32:47.478 --> 01:32:50.063
[ORDERS IN JAPANESE]
I'll tell you, I'll tell you.

01:32:51.607 --> 01:32:54.401
I'll tell you everything
we heard on the radio.

01:32:54.735 --> 01:32:56.319
I'll tell you the truth.

01:33:00.324 --> 01:33:03.118
While you're here
building your railway

01:33:04.370 --> 01:33:07.622
American submarines
are destroying your shipping.

01:33:07.999 --> 01:33:11.376
There's shortages
of food and fuel all over Japan.

01:33:11.752 --> 01:33:14.379
American planes
are bombing your cities,

01:33:14.463 --> 01:33:16.214
destroying your bridges,

01:33:16.882 --> 01:33:18.258
your roads,

01:33:19.010 --> 01:33:20.218
your hospitals.

01:33:21.637 --> 01:33:23.847
And there's no one to stop them.

01:33:26.183 --> 01:33:27.851
Your homes are burning

01:33:30.062 --> 01:33:32.314
and your families are starving.

01:33:37.987 --> 01:33:41.448
That is what I heard
on the radio.

01:33:45.536 --> 01:33:46.745
You're a liar.

01:33:49.290 --> 01:33:50.624
You tell lies.

01:33:51.334 --> 01:33:53.251
You have no honour.

01:33:55.588 --> 01:33:57.172
Your army is defeated.

01:33:58.299 --> 01:34:01.176
You surrender like dogs.
Look at you.

01:34:02.219 --> 01:34:04.471
You should be ashamed
to be alive.

01:34:06.098 --> 01:34:07.974
If my army was defeated,

01:34:09.101 --> 01:34:11.686
I would take my life
to save my honour.

01:34:13.856 --> 01:34:16.024
You're getting your chance.

01:34:16.984 --> 01:34:18.443
Any day now.

01:34:21.155 --> 01:34:23.698
[SPEAKS IN JAPANESE]

01:34:26.410 --> 01:34:28.620
[SHOUTS IN JAPANESE]

01:34:30.081 --> 01:34:32.666
[SLAP, NAGASE YELLS]

01:34:32.833 --> 01:34:34.584
[SLOW MUSIC]

01:35:05.199 --> 01:35:07.409
[MUSIC STOPS]

01:35:14.667 --> 01:35:17.335
My mother was already dead,
as it happens.

01:35:21.757 --> 01:35:22.966
All through the war,

01:35:24.051 --> 01:35:26.428
I wrote letters home
to a dead woman.

01:35:37.940 --> 01:35:39.607
What do you tell people?

01:35:42.528 --> 01:35:44.320
About what you did to us?

01:35:50.327 --> 01:35:52.537
We do not talk about it.

01:35:53.581 --> 01:35:56.499
No one will talk about it.

01:36:01.130 --> 01:36:02.130
Nor do we.

01:36:04.425 --> 01:36:05.759
And you know why?

01:36:08.804 --> 01:36:10.889
Because no one would believe it.

01:36:11.515 --> 01:36:14.142
No one would believe
what you did to us.

01:36:21.108 --> 01:36:24.444
You treated us like animals
because we surrendered.

01:36:26.822 --> 01:36:28.656
You said you'd rather die...

01:36:29.158 --> 01:36:30.992
than live without honour.

01:36:33.746 --> 01:36:35.163
But you didn't die.

01:36:40.419 --> 01:36:42.170
It was a lie they told us.

01:36:45.508 --> 01:36:46.841
It was all lies.

01:36:49.470 --> 01:36:50.470
[SNIFFS]

01:36:50.554 --> 01:36:52.138
That we would win.

01:36:54.350 --> 01:36:56.684
We would have honour.

01:37:01.148 --> 01:37:02.565
They lied to us.

01:37:04.944 --> 01:37:07.028
Only you told me the truth.

01:37:09.657 --> 01:37:12.492
No matter what we did to you,

01:37:12.952 --> 01:37:14.452
you held on.

01:37:19.625 --> 01:37:21.459
You showed me that

01:37:23.671 --> 01:37:26.631
nothing's worth more
than this life.

01:37:32.972 --> 01:37:34.013
Finlay...

01:37:39.270 --> 01:37:40.520
He was my friend.

01:37:41.689 --> 01:37:43.273
He was a prisoner here.

01:37:48.737 --> 01:37:50.530
He put your life in my hands.

01:37:53.534 --> 01:37:55.243
He wanted an end to this.

01:37:57.204 --> 01:37:58.204
Maybe...

01:38:00.374 --> 01:38:02.750
that is why I am alive.

01:38:05.045 --> 01:38:06.170
For this day.

01:38:08.632 --> 01:38:10.258
Maybe we both lived...

01:38:11.927 --> 01:38:12.969
for this day.

01:38:13.053 --> 01:38:15.430
[SLOW MUSIC]

01:38:22.187 --> 01:38:23.646
You can make an end.

01:38:27.776 --> 01:38:30.111
You are a soldier, Lomax.

01:38:38.621 --> 01:38:40.121
You never surrendered.

01:38:46.337 --> 01:38:48.004
I'm still at war.

01:39:14.281 --> 01:39:16.574
[MUSIC BUILDS UP]

01:39:53.445 --> 01:39:54.988
[MUSIC PAUSES]

01:39:58.826 --> 01:40:01.202
[MUSIC SLOWLY RESUMES]

01:40:59.595 --> 01:41:01.054
I thought I'd lost you.

01:41:18.572 --> 01:41:21.115
When Finlay died, I was scared.

01:41:23.577 --> 01:41:26.496
I was scared that the same
might happen to you.

01:41:30.209 --> 01:41:32.168
It was different for Finlay.

01:41:35.089 --> 01:41:36.631
He didn't have you.

01:42:33.689 --> 01:42:35.898
[NAGASE:]
Dear Mr Lomax,

01:42:37.151 --> 01:42:40.820
I was a member of
the Imperial Japanese Army.

01:42:44.533 --> 01:42:49.620
We treated you and your
countrymen very, very badly.

01:42:53.167 --> 01:42:56.335
It is a long time since
the war ended,

01:42:59.506 --> 01:43:00.631
but for me

01:43:02.801 --> 01:43:04.677
it is a time of suffering.

01:43:08.807 --> 01:43:10.766
The dagger of our meeting

01:43:11.018 --> 01:43:13.519
thrust deep into my heart.

01:43:17.357 --> 01:43:19.317
I never forgot you.

01:43:22.279 --> 01:43:24.071
I remember your face,

01:43:27.242 --> 01:43:28.242
your arms,

01:43:31.079 --> 01:43:32.413
your eyes.

01:43:38.587 --> 01:43:40.046
I have to go back.

01:43:43.175 --> 01:43:44.884
I want you to come with me.

01:44:20.379 --> 01:44:22.088
[MUSIC STOPS,
BIRDS CHIRP]

01:44:27.886 --> 01:44:30.096
I wouldn't have lasted a day here.

01:44:31.974 --> 01:44:33.557
If you'd been here,

01:44:34.643 --> 01:44:36.727
you'd have caused quite a stir.

01:44:46.613 --> 01:44:49.073
You'd have outlasted
the lot of us.

01:45:04.298 --> 01:45:12.298
[DISTANT THUNDER]

01:45:43.962 --> 01:45:48.382
[SLOWLY RAIN BEGINS TO FALL]

01:46:00.437 --> 01:46:01.729
I am sorry.

01:46:06.276 --> 01:46:07.485
So sorry.

01:46:16.370 --> 01:46:19.330
I don't want to
live that day anymore.

01:46:25.295 --> 01:46:26.504
Neither do I.

01:46:31.343 --> 01:46:34.053
[SLOW MUSIC]

01:47:02.916 --> 01:47:04.083
Dear Mr Nagase,

01:47:05.836 --> 01:47:08.671
the war has been over
for many years.

01:47:11.007 --> 01:47:12.425
I have suffered much.

01:47:14.302 --> 01:47:16.595
But I know
you have suffered too.

01:47:16.680 --> 01:47:18.139
[SOBS]

01:47:20.350 --> 01:47:22.685
And you have been
most courageous

01:47:23.061 --> 01:47:24.603
and brave

01:47:25.147 --> 01:47:27.314
in working for reconciliation.

01:47:30.402 --> 01:47:31.485
Sorry.

01:47:32.571 --> 01:47:34.530
While I cannot forget

01:47:34.948 --> 01:47:37.408
what happened in Kanchanaburi,

01:47:39.035 --> 01:47:40.453
I assure you

01:47:41.079 --> 01:47:42.705
of my total forgiveness.

01:47:54.634 --> 01:47:56.802
Sometime the hating has to stop.

01:56:14.050 --> 01:56:15.884
[MUSIC STOPS]

